                            <author>Ps. Alcuinus / Ps. Arno Salisburgensis</author>
                            <rubric>Ordo uel breuis explanatio de <sic>caticizandis</sic> rudibus</rubric>
                            <incipit>Primo ergo in catecizandis rudibus apostolicum oportet intueri sermonem</incipit>
                            <explicit>sicut pater noster caelestis perfectus est.</explicit>
                            <note>Title and first three lines written in black ink by one hand; rest in brown ink in a second hand.</note>
                            <filiation>The work is known in three recensions: 1) in <ref type="altMs" target="https://mdz-nbn-resolving.de/details:bsb00047265">Munich, Bayerische Staatsbibliothek, Clm 6325</ref>, ff. 134v-142v (Freising, 820 - 830) and its copy <ref type="altMs" target="http://mdz-nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:bvb:12-bsb00047264-2">Munich, Bayerische Staatsbibliothek, Clm 6324</ref>, ff. 98v-107r (Freising, 850 - 860); 2) in our manuscript; and 3) in <ref type="altMs">Rouen, Bibliothèque Jacques Villon (olim Bibliothèque Municipale), 469 (A. 214)</ref>, ff. 121v-135r (Fecamp, end of 11<hi rend="sup">th</hi> c. or beginning of the 12<hi rend="sup">th</hi>). According to Bouhot, the recension preserved in the Munich MSS is an abridgment of the version preserved in the Vienna MS. The longer version preserved in the Rouen MS follows more rigorously the plan set in Alcuin's letter to Charlemagne from 798 (<title>Primo paganus</title>). This text serves also as terminus post quem for the original composition . The recension in the Vienna MS represents probably the answer of Arno of Salzburg on Charlemagne's enquiry from 812. So the <title>Ordo</title> was written in the beginning of the ninth century. The version of the Vienna MS and the abridgment found in the Munich MSS is probably from the end of the first third of the ninth century (terminus ante quem based on B. Bischoff's dating of Munich Clm 6325).</filiation>
                            
                            <!--                            Compare with Augustine's De de catechizandis rudibus (Lit.: https://www.brepolsonline.net/doi/pdf/10.1484/J.RA.5.102393; Edition in PL: https://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/02m/0354-0430,_Augustinus,_De_Catechizandis_Rudibus,_MLT.pdf; FR and DE translation in https://bkv.unifr.ch/works/130
                            Check if text on ff. 3r-22r identical with In libro ad conpetentes by Nicetas Remesianensis (In PL LII and LXVIII under the names of Nicetas of Aquileia and Nicetius of Treves); (Stegmüller Nr. 5659) For possible reconstruction of Niceta's work see Burn and Gamber. According to Burn 1905: The Libelli instructionis or Books of instruction for candidates for baptism - in six books; known only in part. Four fragments of Book I - How candidates who seek to obtain grace of baptism ought to act (PL 52) and one fragment of Book II on the errors of the gentiles. The content is reported by Gennadius De viris illustribus cap. 22
                            The fragments make part of the Ordo de catechizandis rudibus (Order of Catechising) which is know to exist in three recensions
                            1) The two Munich MSS from Freising datable to the 9th and 10th c. Text published in the Zeitschrift für Kirchengeschichte 25, p. 145; contain only Fragments 1, 3 and 4. Suggestion that this may be the reply of Arno of Salzburg to the enquiry which was made by Charles the Great in 812.
                            2) Cod. 1370 - Fragments 1-6 published so by Mai. This recension of the Ordo contains additional quotations from Alcuin, Athanasius, Leo and Augustine, as well as a sermon on the Creed (in Rouen longer and so identified as fragment of the original Book 5)
                            3) Rouen 469 from the 11th or 12th c. 
                            The editor of each recension had Niceta's works in his hands, and added special quotations.
                            On such text see <bibl>Bouhot, Jean-Paul. ‘Explications du rituel baptismal à l’époque carolingienne’. Revue d’Etudes Augustiniennes et Patristiques 24, no. 3–4 (January 1978): 278–301. https://doi.org/10.1484/J.REA.5.104365.</bibl> : many text showing the efforts for religious instruction - not cherished because of their lack of originality, form, and anonymity. Form of explanation of the rites, prayers, holy mass and baptism, the symbols of the apostles, symbol Quicumque. Often florilegia. Catechise - some edited. Buhot makes an inventary for the explanations on the baptism from the Carolingian period but based on already edited texts.
                            -->
